Simulating Data from a N-State HMM

Lets simulate data from an HMM. As mentioned before, we need to specify a few things:

  • the number of states \(N\)
  • the state-dependent distributions, \(f(X_t | C_t = n)\)
  • the transition probabiility matrix
  • the initial state distribution

Well make use of the library tidyverse, which includes ggplot2, to plot our data.

library(tidyverse)

## Specify the number of states ---------------
N <- 2

## Specify the initial distribution -----------
init <- rep(1/N, N)

## Specify the transition probability matrix ----
tpm <- matrix(c(0.8, 0.2, 
                0.3, 0.7), 
              byrow=T, nrow=2)

## Specify the state-dependent distribution + values of parameters
## Normal(mean, standard deviation)
mu <- c(5, 10)
sd <- c(2, 1)

Now lets simulate data from our 2-state HMM with normal state-dependent distributions.

# Length of the time series
len <- 1000

states <- numeric(len)
obs <- numeric(len)

# Simulating states
states[1] <- sample(size=1, x = 1:N, prob = init)

for(j in 2:len){
  states[j] <- sample(size=1, x = 1:N, prob = tpm[states[j-1],])
}

# Simulating observations
obs <- rnorm(len, mean=mu[states], sd = sd[states])
